- - - ( Objects ) - - - 



- ( Example (1) All property values ):
• str: "hello",
• num: 123,
• bool: true,
• nul: null,
• undef: undefined,
• obj: { key: "value" },
• arr: [1, 2, 3],
• func: function() { return "hi"; },
• sym: Symbol("id"),
• big: 123

- null and undefined are the same, their use cases are
• a variable that has null, means value is empty 
• a variable that has undefined, means value is not yet / will be set 



- ( Example (2) Create Empty Object ):

// ( Both Syntax are the same )
• const person = { }; 
• const person = new Object( );

// Add Properties to empty Object
• person.firstName = "John";
• person.lastName = "Doe";
• person.age = 50;
• person.eyeColor = "blue";



- ( Example (3) Create & Initialize Object ):

• const person = {
  firstName : "John", 
  lastName : "Doe", 
  age : 50, 
  eyeColor : "blue"
  };



- ( Example (4) Object Property Accessibility ):

// Accessing Object Properties
• objectName.propertyName;
• objectName["propertyName"];

// Accessing Nested Object Properties
• objectName.propertyName.propertyName;
• objectName["propertyName"]["propertyName"];

// Adding new Property in Object
• person.nationality = "English"; 

- New properties, must have a value, otherwise they won't get added

- New Properties, must have a different name, otherwise they'll
  juts overwrite the value of the property that's already present 

// Delete Object Properties
• delete objectName.propertyName
• delete objectName["propertyName"]



- ( Example (5) Object methods ):

• const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  fullName: function() { return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName; }
};

- "this" refers to the object it's in

// Accessing / Invoking Object Method, Output: John Doe
• console.log( person.fullName() ); 

// /Adding a Method to an Object
• obj.Property = function () { return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName; }; //Adds a new property with a method as a value
• obj.PresentProperty = function () { return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName; }; //Overwrites property value



- ( Example (6) Object Values & Entries ):

- Object.values( object ); // returns an array of values from an object
  
• Example: [ value1, value2, ... ]


- Object.entries( object ); // returns an array from the property values

• Example: [ [key1, value1], [key2, value2], ... ]

• Example used in a loop: 
   for(let [key, value] of Object.entries(person)) { console.log(key, value); }



- ( Example (7) Object Constructor Functions ):

- function Person(first, last, age, eye) {
 this.firstName = first;
 this.lastName = last;
 this.age = age;
 this.eyeColor = eye;
} 
// Values in this object depends on values passed in parameters, but you can create / assign it default values 

- Using the function to create Objects   

• const myFather = new Person("John", "Doe", 50, "blue");
• const myMother = new Person("Sally", "Rally", 48, "green");
• const mySister = new Person("Anna", "Rally", 18, "green");
• const mySelf = new Person("Johnny", "Rally", 22, "green");

- Adding a new method must be done to the constructor function prototype:

• Person.prototype.changeName = function (name) { this.lastName = name; } // Method added to the constructor function

• myMother.changeName("Doe"); // Filling the parameter of the method in the constructor function